  "opinion": "As a retired man living in Rome, I've spent many years learning how to navigate conversations on sensitive topics like COVID vaccines. With my high conscientiousness but low openness score from the Big Five personality test, I tend to stick to what's familiar and avoid getting overwhelmed by new information. My anxiety sometimes makes these discussions tricky because they involve so much uncertainty about health and safety.\n\nFirstly, when people bring up COVID or any healthcare topic in our chats here on social media—mostly family gatherings but occasionally with friends too—I try not to jump straight into arguments unless I'm sure of what we're talking about. We all have different experiences: some might be grandparents worried about their grandchildren getting sick easily while others could be younger colleagues pushing back against the idea that vaccines aren't necessary anymore.\n\nI've found it helpful to start by asking questions if I don't feel confident myself, like 'What specific concerns are you thinking of?' or maybe suggesting we look at official sources for clarity. But with my low agreeableness score—though that might be an exaggeration in this context—I won’t hesitate to gently point out where misinformation is floating around online.\n\nFor example, last week when someone shared rumors about the vaccines causing infertility on Facebook during our virtual family get-together (since some kids are away for university now), I calmly brought up how facts matter more than scary stories. It helps that my Hindu faith teaches us to be cautious with health matters anyway; sometimes sticking to traditional ways feels safer.\n\nBut managing anxiety is key here. If the conversation gets too heated, which it occasionally does when discussing something as personal and uncertain like this pandemic stuff, I take a step back or change the subject temporarily until things settle down.",
